---
// hidden-history/syllabus.astro — the course syllabus as a clean, printable page.
// Content mirrors the official syllabus doc. NOTE: verify grading scale against
// the 2026-27 handbook before the first day — this uses the 2025-26 draft.
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';

const units = [
  { when: 'weeks 1–3', name: 'The Official Story vs. The Rumor', what: 'Roswell, Area 51, and the foundations of evidence.', habit: 'question' },
  { when: 'weeks 4–6', name: 'Follow the Evidence', what: 'Watergate and the "Paul is dead" rumor.', habit: 'research' },
  { when: 'weeks 7–9', name: 'Reading the Record', what: 'The Pentagon Papers and the Pearl Harbor advance-knowledge claims.', habit: 'analyze' },
  { when: 'weeks 10–12', name: 'Trust and Verify', what: 'MKUltra and the mind-control myths; fact-checking in the social media age.', habit: 'evaluate' },
  { when: 'weeks 13–15', name: 'Watching the Watchers', what: 'COINTELPRO and shadow-government myths; the surveillance debate.', habit: 'debate' },
  { when: 'weeks 16–18', name: 'The Verdict', what: 'Iran-Contra, the JFK files, the moon-landing autopsy, and your Case File capstone.', habit: 'think critically' },
];

const weights = [
  { part: 'Unit tests and assessments', pct: '25%' },
  { part: 'Exercises, logs, and fact-check portfolios', pct: '25%' },
  { part: 'Capstone Case File project', pct: '20%' },
  { part: 'Debate and seminar participation', pct: '10%' },
  { part: 'Semester exam or equivalent', pct: '20%' },
];
---

<Base title="hidden history — syllabus" description="hidden history: conspiracies, cover-ups, and historical evidence — course syllabus.">
  <p class="font-mono text-xs lowercase text-ink-soft">semester elective · grades 10–12 · mr. auch · mt. morris schools · 2026-27</p>
  <h1 class="mt-2 font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold lowercase tracking-tight">
    hidden history<span class="text-accent">.</span> <span class="text-ink-soft">the syllabus</span>
  </h1>

  <div class="mt-8 max-w-2xl space-y-5 leading-relaxed">
    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase">what this course is</h2>
    <p>
      History is full of moments when the official story turned out to be wrong — and just as many moments when a
      juicy rumor turned out to be nothing at all. This semester elective is built around a single skill that matters
      more every year: separating verified historical fact from speculation, rumor, and misinformation. We investigate
      documented American scandals and cover-ups — Watergate, the Pentagon Papers, COINTELPRO, MKUltra, Iran-Contra —
      and examine the declassified JFK files alongside famous claims that have not held up. Along the way you learn
      how historians, journalists, and investigators actually work: weighing sources, corroborating claims, and
      tracing how stories spread and mutate through the media of their era.
    </p>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase pt-4">the map</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-2">
      {units.map((u) => (
        <li class="flex gap-3 items-baseline border-b-2 border-line pb-2">
          <span class="font-mono text-xs text-accent shrink-0 w-24">{u.when}</span>
          <div>
            <span class="font-semibold">{u.name}</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-ink-soft"> — {u.what}</span>
            <span class="ml-1 text-xs font-mono lowercase text-accent">habit: {u.habit}</span>
          </div>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase pt-4">the four verdicts</h2>
    <p>
      Every claim we study gets one of four verdicts, and you are graded on how you reach yours, not just what it is:
      <strong>confirmed</strong> (supported by reliable documents, testimony, physical evidence, or multiple
      independent sources), <strong>debunked</strong> (reliable evidence contradicts it),
      <strong>misleading</strong> (true or partly true material framed to create a false impression), or
      <strong>unproven</strong> (the available reliable evidence is insufficient). An honest "unproven" backed by good
      research beats a confident answer backed by nothing — in this class and in life.
    </p>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase pt-4">grading</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-ink-soft">
      Grades are calculated with points, weighted as below. Letter grades follow the student handbook
      (93–100 A, 90–92 A−, 87–89 B+, 83–86 B, 80–82 B−, 77–79 C+, 73–76 C, 70–72 C−, 67–69 D+, 63–66 D, 60–62 D−, below 60 F).
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-1">
      {weights.map((w) => (
        <li class="flex justify-between border-b-2 border-line pb-1 text-sm">
          <span>{w.part}</span>
          <span class="font-mono text-accent">{w.pct}</span>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase pt-4">the two class rules</h2>
    <p>
      (1) <strong>We attack claims, never people.</strong> In this course you will sometimes discover a belief you hold
      doesn't survive the evidence — that happens to everyone, including historians, and it is treated as a win, not
      an embarrassment. (2) <strong>Sources or it didn't happen.</strong> Any factual claim made in discussion or
      debate can be challenged with "what's your source?" — including claims made by the teacher.
    </p>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase pt-4">what to bring</h2>
    <p>
      A writing utensil, a folder or binder for handouts and logs, and your assigned device on lab days. Most readings
      are primary sources provided in class.
    </p>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase pt-4">a note for families</h2>
    <p>
      This course teaches students how to evaluate evidence, using documented history — including declassified
      government programs — and famous claims that failed under scrutiny. Case studies draw on public government
      archives, original journalism, and established scholarship. The goal is neither cynicism nor blind trust: it is
      the ability to tell proof from noise. Questions are always welcome.
    </p>

    <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold lowercase pt-4">attendance</h2>
    <p>
      This course is heavily built on in-class labs, discussions, and team investigation work that cannot be fully
      made up at home. Poor attendance usually results in poor grades — follow the attendance policy.
    </p>

    <p class="pt-4 print:hidden">
      <a href="/hidden-history/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-dark underline underline-offset-4">← back to hidden history</a>
    </p>
  </div>

  <style is:global>
    @media print {
      header, footer { display: none !important; }
      main { padding: 0 !important; }
    }
  </style>
</Base>
